Example of Vector Autoregressive Models (VAR)¶

We will use the number of passengers and the number of flights. Our aim is to understand the dynamic relationship between these two variables over time.

Stationary¶

Before implementing the VAR we need to check also for stationarity in the other series, that is, the number of passengers series.

In the number of flights we have done it already in the project implementing a seasonal difference to make it stationary

Modelling¶

Before perform the VAR model, we needed to create a new dataframe with both series.

In [ ]:
# Convert the differenced series into a DataFrame
df_diff = pd.DataFrame({'Flt_diffa12': flt_diffa12, 'Pax_diffa12': pax_diffa12})

# Drop missing values if any
df_diff.dropna(inplace=True)

The next step was to find the right VAR(p) order, based on the AIC and BIC criterion. We created a loop to find this AIC and BIC of each p-order.

In [ ]:
# Estimate the VAR model
# Selecting the order (p) of the VAR model
model = VAR(df_diff)
for i in range(1, 10):
    result = model.fit(i)
    print('Order =', i)
    print('AIC : ', result.aic)
    print('BIC : ', result.bic)

The VAR(p) with the lowest AIC and BIC is the one with order 9, so we implemented the VAR model with this order.

In [ ]:
# Estimate the VAR model
# Selecting the order (p) of the VAR model
var_model = VAR(df_diff)
selected_order = 9  # selected order is 9 based on lowest AIC/BIC

# Fitting the model with the selected order
model_fitted = var_model.fit(selected_order)
print(model_fitted.summary())

Results for each equation:

For each equation, the coefficients, standard errors, t-statistics, and probabilities are presented for each lag term. Each coefficient represents the effect of the corresponding lagged variable on the current variable.

The probability (prob) column represents the p-value associated with each coefficient. Lower values indicate greater significance. For example, in the equation for Flt_diffa12, the coefficient of L1.Flt_diffa12 is -5.075640 with a very low p-value (prob=0.000), indicating that the lagged value of Flt_diffa12 has a significant impact on the current value of Flt_diffa12.

Correlation matrix of residuals:

This matrix shows the correlation between the residuals of Flt_diffa12 and Pax_diffa12. A high correlation suggests that there may be some unexplained relationship between the two variables not captured by the model. Here, the correlation coefficient is 0.771658, which means that the two series are strong correlated between the residuals of the two equations.

Impulse Response Analysis¶

In a VAR model, impulse response analysis examines the dynamic response of each variable in the system to a one-time shock in one of the variables, while holding all other variables constant.

In [ ]:
# Perform Impulse Response Analysis
impulse_response = model_fitted.irf(10)  # Compute impulse responses for 10 periods

# Plot the Impulse Response Functions
impulse_response.plot(orth=True)  # Plot orthogonalized impulse response functions
plt.xlabel('Time Periods')  # Set label for the x-axis
plt.ylabel('Response')  # Set label for the y-axis
plt.title('Impulse Response Analysis')  # Set title for the plot
plt.grid(True)  # Add grid lines to the plot
plt.show()  # Display the plot

In general, we observed that the shock of the 'Flt_diffa12' to the same series, oscillate over the periods, with high peaks. The situation with 'Pax_diffa12' is exactly the same. However, the shocks of 'Pax_diffa12' are almost stable near to zero for the first 8 periods. Then, in the perdiod 8 we had a positive shock that affect positive to the number of flights. After this shock, we had a negative shock with a plunge in the final period. For the shock of flights to the number of passangers, the response oscillate with the shock.

Forecast error variance decomposition (FEVD)¶

Is a part of structural analysis which "decomposes" the variance of the forecast error into the contributions from specific exogenous shocks.

Intuitively this is useful because it demonstrates how important a shock is in explaining the variations of the variables in the model. Additionally, shows how that importance changes over time. For example, some shocks may not be responsible for variations in the short-run but may cause longer-term fluctuations.

In [ ]:
# FEVD
fevd = model_fitted.fevd(5)
fevd.summary()

FEVD for Flt_diffa12
     Flt_diffa12  Pax_diffa12

3       0.999860     0.000140
4       0.999586     0.000414

FEVD for Pax_diffa12
     Flt_diffa12  Pax_diffa12
0       0.595457     0.404543
1       0.599842     0.400158
2       0.603864     0.396136
3       0.604846     0.395154
4       0.598786     0.401214
  • At period 0, Flt_diffa12 explains 100% of the forecast error variance, while Pax_diffa12 explains 0%. This suggests that, initially, all the forecast error variance in Flt_diffa12 is due to its own shocks, with no contribution from Pax_diffa12.
  • At period 1, Flt_diffa12 still explains nearly all (99.9996%) of the forecast error variance, with a very minor contribution (0.0004%) from Pax_diffa12.
  • At period 2, Flt_diffa12 continues to explain the vast majority (99.9968%) of the forecast error variance, with a slightly increased contribution (0.0032%) from Pax_diffa12.
  • At period 3, Flt_diffa12 explains 99.986% of the forecast error variance, with a minor contribution (0.014%) from Pax_diffa12.
  • By period 4, Flt_diffa12 still dominates, explaining 99.9586% of the forecast error variance, with a small contribution (0.0414%) from Pax_diffa12.

In summary, Flt_diffa12 has a significantly higher impact on explaining the forecast error variance compared to Pax_diffa12 across different forecast horizons.
